    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Never published before this edition.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=".."><name><supplied reason="lost">Α</supplied>ἰγλάνωρ</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=".."><name nymRef="#Νίκαιος">Νικαίω</name></persName></persName>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Aiglanôr fils de Nikaios.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Aiglanor son of Nikaios.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Aiglanor figlio di Nikaios.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p/>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
             <p>This base, copied in 1981 by members of the French archaeological mission at Apollonia who were walking through the West Necropolis of Cyrene, was never seen again and does not seem to 
                 have been brought to the Department of Antiquities.</p>
             <p>Although Aiglanor is a very common name at Cyrene, it seems plausible on behalf of the lettering that this Aiglanor son of Nikaios was related to Nikaios son of Aiglanor mentioned as commander of a batallion of <foreign xml:lang="italic">paraibatai</foreign> 
             in the list <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr084000</ref> at line 123. However if ever the relation is plausible, we cannot decide whether our Aiglanor was the father or the son of the commander.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
